%%%%%% Bidding After 1 of a Major Opening is Doubled
cs|1|fp|2|cp|4|at|
^-{    Bidding After 1 of a Major Opening is Doubled    }
^-|CP||FP||CS||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Several important points I like to emphasize. First, conventions such as 2/1 game forcing, 1NT forcing, Jacoby 2NT, and inverted minors all should be off after an opponent's takeout double. And finally Bergen Raises are off after competition (unless you agree otherwise).|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

First, let me explain what is standard and played by most people. You need to learn it if you are going to play with unfamiliar partners. Afterward, I will outline the way I play it.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

In what is standard, bids at the 1-level over a takeout double (e.g. 1@h-x-1@s) show the same thing as if there were not a takeout double. They show at least a 4-card suit and at least 6 points. They have no upper limit in terms of either HCP or the number of cards in the suit bid. And they are forcing. |
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

However, bids at the 2-level (e.g. 1@h-x-2@C) are weak. They show less than 10 points and a 5+ card suit. They are not forcing. If you have 10 points and a suit that you must bid at the 2-level, then you redouble. Having said that, many players screw it up and think new suits are always forcing whether responder bids at the 1-level or 2-level (e.g. many players mistakenly think 1@h-X-2@C is forcing, even though it should be weak and is definitely not forcing).|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

I personally find this rather confusing. So I play that if you don't redouble or bid Jordan 2N over a takeout double you can't have 10 points. Therefore, after a double, new suits by responder are not forcing, whether or not they are at the 1-level. I think my style is a lot simpler and easier to play than what is played by most. Nevertheless, you need learn that style if you want to play with unfamiliar partners. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


NT||
