cs|1|fp|2|cp|4|at|
^-{    Bidding After 1 of a Major Opening is Doubled    }
^-|CP||FP||CS||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|In my style, on the other hand, a new bid by responder after a takeout double shows less than 10 points. For example 1@H-X-1@S or 1@H-X-2@C are less than 10 points—keep that in mind. For ease of explanation let us divide the responder's hand in two categories:|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


hT|g|AT|^CA. Hands with 6-9 points.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


hT|g|AT|^CA. Hands with 6-9 points.
^cB. Hands with 10+ points.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

In category A—with 6-9 and support for partner's suit you bid based on the Law of Total tricks |CP|1|AT|^*Htiny.cc/087z9w^*N|CP||AT|.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

Bid 2 with 3-card support (just like after an overcall).|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

Bid 3 with 4-card support and less than a limit raise. In competition you want to play weak jump raises. Remember the Law of Total Tricks is your friend :).|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

Bid 4 with 5-card support.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

In category B—
^cREDOUBLE with 10+ points and less than 3-card support.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

^cREDOUBLE with 10+ points and with 3-card support.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


AT|

^cBid 2NT (Jordan 2NT) with 4-card support and limit raise or better (10+).|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

^B@2Some experts recommend bidding redouble with 10 points holding less than 3-card support and bid 2NT with 3+ card support and limit raise or better. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

Finally, another important note is the 1@H/1@S-double-1N. In this auction 1NT promises 8-11.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


AT|

Let us look at some examples for 1 of a major followed by take out double. |
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


